Introduction

Background

There is a high risk of landing overrun if the aircraft’s landing distance exceeds the available distance. The landing distance required is affected by many factors. We use the simulated data provided by Professor Dr. Liu to study the factors involved and how they would impact the landing distance of a commercial flight.

Motivation

To reduce landing overrun

Goal

To study what factors and how they would impact the landing distance of a commercial flight

Steps Followed

  1. Understanding and importing the data
  2. Merging the data
  3. Removing the duplicates and abnormal values
  4. Handling missing values
  5. Correlation analysis with respect to the target feature
  6. Identifying the significant parameters
  7. Fitting a linear regression model to the get the relationship between independent variables and target feature
  8. Model Diagonistic and Re fitting

Data Preparation

Collection of Data

The data has been simulated from statistical models. It is provided in two excel sheets with a total of 950 records of commercial flight observations - the landing distance and other parameters.

Data Description

The data is provided in two excel files:

  1. FAA2.xls : Excel file has 800 records and 8 columns. Column names : aircraft , duration, no_pasg, speed_ground, speed_air, height, pitch,

  2. FAA2.xls : Excel file has 150 records and 7 columns. Column names: aircraft , no_pasg, speed_ground, speed_air, height, pitch, distance.

Column description

  • Aircraft: The make of an aircraft (Boeing or Airbus).
  • Duration: Flight duration between taking off and landing. The duration of a normal flight should always be greater than 40min.
  • No_pasg : The number of passengers in a flight.
  • Speed_ground (in miles per hour): The ground speed of an aircraft when passing over the threshold of the runway. If its value is less than 30MPH or greater than 140MPH, then the landing would be considered as abnormal.
  • Speed_air (in miles per hour): The air speed of an aircraft when passing over the threshold of the runway. If its value is less than 30MPH or greater than 140MPH, then the landing would be considered as abnormal.
  • Height (in meters): The height of an aircraft when it is passing over the threshold of the runway. The landing aircraft is required to be at least 6 meters high at the threshold of the runway.
  • Pitch (in degrees): Pitch angle of an aircraft when it is passing over the threshold of the runway.
  • Distance (in feet): The landing distance of an aircraft. More specifically, it refers to the distance between the threshold of the runway and the point where the aircraft can be fully stopped. The length of the airport runway is typically less than 6000 feet.

Removing abnormal values

Abnormal value criteria specified in the data dictionary: * The duration should be greater than 40 mins hence we need to remove the rows which do not follow the condition. * Height has values in negative as captured by the minimum, hence we will be removing the height < 6 meters. * Since it is given that the length of the runway is typically 6000 feet, we want to remove landing distance values > 6000 as it is the target feature and has a high significance. * Speed ground values less than 30 and greater than 140 are considered abnormal and hence we will be removing that.

data<-data[data$duration>=40 || is.na(data$duration)==TRUE,]
data<-data[data$speed_ground>=30 && data$speed_ground<=140,]
data<-data[data$height>=6,]
data<-data[data$distance<=6000,]
#view(data)

Investigating the speed_air missing values (Should we use imputation ? )

Speed_air has the most number of missing values. Intuitively the speed_air and speed_ground seems to have a correlation based on a glance at few records. Let’s look at the Speed_air and speed_ground correlation :

scatter.smooth(data$speed_air,data$speed_ground)

cor(data[which(is.na(data$speed_air)==FALSE),c(4,5)])
##              speed_ground speed_air
## speed_ground    1.0000000 0.9879355
## speed_air       0.9879355 1.0000000

The variables speed_air and speed_ground have a high correlation. The Proc means observations show that the minimum of speed_ground is 33 and the minimum of speed_air (the column with a maximum number of missing values) is 90. Knowing the high correlation between the two variables and large variance between the minimum values, it seems that the variability of the actual speed_air is not covered by the data available.

Plotting the speed_air:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
boxplot(data$speed_air)
hist(data$speed_air)

The speed air does not have values below 90 -> speed_air has a truncated distribution. Hence, it is not a good idea to do imputation here.

Summary

  • The two datasets had a mix of data for Airbus and Boeing. The number of unique records in FAA2 was 50. Hence, we merged the two datasets.
  • The summary statistics of variables by aircraft were quite similar hence we can analyze both the aircraft data together.
  • The final dataset (air) has a total of 838 rows - after removing duplicates and abnormal values. The following columns have missing values: Duration - 6 % missing values ( 50 records missing). Speed_air - 75% missing values ( 632 records missing).
  • All the duration missing values are for Airbus records.
  • Speed_air has a high correlation with speed_ground
  • Speed_air has a truncated distribution hence imputation is not a good idea for this case.

Statistical Modeling

We need to map three features: speed_ground, height , pitch and aircraft to the target feature distance. Since the relationship seems to be linear in our prior observations. We will be using linear regression for multiple variables.

Linear Regression: A linear model for our case will be of the form Y = \(b_0\) + \(b_1\) \(x_1\) + \(b_2\) \(x_2\)…\(b_n\) \(x_n\) + ε. The constant \(b_0\) is called the intercept and the coefficients \(b_1\),.. \(b_n\) are the parameter estimates for the variables \(x_1\),\(x_2\)… \(x_n\) respectively. The ε is the error term.

model1<-(lm(distance~., data = data))

summary(model1)

Variable Selection

We will try to use Stepwise regression to get out the best model.

attach(data)
y<-distance
x1<-aircraft
x2<-duration
x3<-no_pasg
x4<-speed_ground
x5<-height
x6<-pitch

Forward Selection

add1(lm(y~1,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
add1(lm(y~x1,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
add1(lm(y~x1+x4,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
add1(lm(y~x1+x4+x5,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
add1(lm(y~x1+x4+x5+x6,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
add1(lm(y~x1+x4+x5+x6+x3,data=data), y~x1+x2+x3+x4+x5+x6, test="F")
model3<-lm(y~x1+x4+x5+x6+x3,data=data)
summary(model3)

Summary

  • The regression model ran with 838 records and the variables taken into account in this iteration are found statistically significant( as proved by the p-value).

  • The R-square value 88.9 is the proportion of variance in the dependent variable (distance) which can be predicted from the independent variables. The Adjusted R square values shows that 88.84% of variability is taken into account.

  • The p value associated with the F value is <0.001 which is lower than 0.05. Hence, we can conclude that the independent variables reliably predict the dependent variable.

  • The relationship between the variables can be explained by the regression equation : distance = -0.37 + 4.051 aircraft - 0.025 no_pasg + 0.321 speed_ground + 0.134 height + 0.569 pitch
